		<itunes:summary>eBay Selling Tips with Andrew Lock.

 For the last year Irsquo;ve been a member of a $14,000 a year Internet Mastermind group, setup by Yanik Silver, whorsquo;s one of the most respected online entrepreneurs in the world of marketing.
You may or may not be familiar with the mastermind concept ndash; either way please pay attention to what Irsquo;m about to tell you. This is extremely important, and if you take note, this tip will be worth your entire annual subscription for many years ndash; thatrsquo;s a promise. Oh, and donrsquo;t worry about the money, yoursquo;re not going to have to fork out 14 grand.
Let me first explain what a mastermind is.
A mastermind group commonly consists of anywhere between 4 and 18 members who have the same goal of expanding their business.  Personally, I believe between six and twelve members is the sweet spot.  You definitely donrsquo;t want any more than 18, and thatrsquo;s probably pushing it.
At each meeting (we meet three times a year), each member is expected to share their best strategies, techniques, and be willing and eager to help everyone else take their business to a much higher level.  When each member contributes in that way, the results are fantastic.  In Yanikrsquo;s group, literally millions of dollars have been created simply by following this concept of being willing to share.  When everyone is willing to give out, they receive back ten fold.
Obviously the dynamics of the group are important.  There needs to be some kind of synergy between members so that everyone respects each other.  In other words, I donrsquo;t believe you should have a mix of newbies and experienced sellers in one group ndash; that would be frustrating to everyone, like a class of students where some feel held back while others are out of their depth.
I can confidently tell you that the mastermind concept has made a bigger impact on my business compared with anything else Irsquo;ve done in recent years.  Why?  Therersquo;s a number of reasons.  First, you surround yourself with a team of expert consultants that analyze your business, take it apart, and then re-build it to be much stronger.  They see things you would never have picked up on in a million years, which when implemented help you take it to another level.  That kind of independent analysis is extremely important because we all get too close to our businesses; we all assume we know the best way of doing something, when often therersquo;s a much better way that was staring us in the face all along ndash; we just didnrsquo;t see it.
Secondly, there is accountability.  At each meeting, you are expected to share your progress with the group.  Without that accountability, you can roam free, and things get done when they get done.  Knowing that you are answerable to the group for what yoursquo;ve accomplished since the last meeting is a strong motivator, and it provides the deadlines that many of us need.
Thirdly, there are the joint venture opportunities. As you get to know the other members, yoursquo;ll see natural ways to work together, and the partnerships that are forged can be extremely useful.  In our group, Irsquo;ve teamed up with a number of members on projects where wersquo;ve combined our strengths to produce and market all kinds of products and services, both on and off the eBay marketplace.
Lastly, there is positive reinforcement.  Itrsquo;s no secret that when you surround yourself with successful people, you become more successful.  It makes sense, and it really does work that way.
By the way, there are many other benefits that I havenrsquo;t talked about and that space simply doesnrsquo;t allow, but I hope by now you understand the power of the mastermind concept.
